@Parity Bit It's true that it's difficult to "fish out" a river. In the PNW, rivers still have some salmon, even though disastrous fishing activity a long time ago devastated the salmon runs. 

I'm not talking about a subsidy. A tax break reduces a company's tax burden, helping to make it more profitable. You wouldn't put out a bounty on carp! If the math on that is lean enough to make it possible but not enough to encourage cheating, I think it could be workable. Perhaps by offering the top-down benefits based not on catch but on third-party survey of fish population in the river. If the population isn't going down, there's no public benefit, so there's no incentive paid. Again, working with one company in a limited area like a river is logistically different from trying to survey rat population in an entire city and dealing with hundreds of individual rat-catchers. 

That said, you've pointed out an excellent case where private enterprise is an inappropriate approach to a problem because of the profit motive, and it may be more effective for the government to run the fishery with the intent to destroy fish and offset the costs by selling the waste material.

