@Fayt Albel 

You are straight up the problem that conservational biologists have been discussing over the past ten years or so. Your obsession with non-native organisms is drawing attention (and thus resources) away from other more pressing issues. The carp‚Äôs impact is localized the mountain pine beetles isn‚Äôt. You realize that right? They are destroying huge swaths of forests and they cause deadfall. That‚Äôs bad, deforestation is a huge contributor to climate change (which could easily be one of the most destructive effects on the environment) and deadfall causes forest fires‚Ä¶ both of those leads to huge emissions of CO2. In the last 20 years they are responsible for nearly a 1000 megatons of CO2 emissions.

That‚Äôs almost 1.5X Canada‚Äôs annual CO2 emissions. Considering those numbers are already included in Canadas emission it‚Äôs likely that up to 5% of Canada‚Äôs carbon emissions is that one species of beetle. The fact you think the carp is worse because it‚Äôs introduced is crazy‚Ä¶ the beetle has a way worse impact and both are equally our fault. That‚Äôs the point of my argument, that we should shift out focus from introduced species and instead focus on problematic species. Will a lot of problematic species be introduced species? Yes, in fact the large majority of them will be (though that percentage will almost certainly lower as climate change ramps up).

@Fayt Albel 

Did you read what I said? Organism colonizing new territory is normal. Yes, sometimes an organism will use another organism to accomplish that task. What you described is natural, it happened before us and it‚Äôll happen after we are gone. For example, Lemurs didn‚Äôt evolve in Madagascar they colonized it (and then diversified). The Fossa in Madagascar also did not originate there and colonized Madagascar. Both of those events dramatically shifted the ecosystems of Madagascar. Bats colonized New Zealand. Large Cats (and other non-marsupial mammals colonized South America. That event destroyed several families of organisms. Like the flightless birds of SA are gone because of it. 

Furthermore, there is a push in conservation biology and ecology to stop calling non-native organisms as invasive, alien, or other derogatory terms. Instead we should call certain species problematic species (specifically ones that cause ecological imbalance that negatively affects us). One reason is that invasive species gives people the impression that this isn‚Äôt a normal phenomenon, it is. There also the fact that native species can become problematic due to climate change. Iirc, there is a species of beetle that is wreaking havoc in British Columbia and it is a native species. The reason why is that they now get an extra reproductive cycle due to the warmer climate. Speaking of climate change, it is likely that organisms will move and colonize new territory at an incredibly fast rate. There are even talks about whether we should assist that happening or not.

